    "content": "return ( ); \"use client\"; interface PlaybookPageLayoutProps children: ReactNode; : PlaybookPageLayoutProps) return ( /* Content */ children /* Footer */ ); // Server Component - no \"use client\" needed return ( /* Header Block */ Operations Playbook Coaching & PIP SOP Standard Operating Procedure for Performance Correction /* Purpose */ Purpose: This document outlines how to address performance issues fairly, consistently, and with proper documentation. The goal is always to help team members succeed — separation is a last resort. /* Section 1: Performance Issue Levels */ 1 . Performance Issue Levels Level Trigger Response Timeline Level 1: Coaching Score 2.0-2.4 OR single issue noticed Verbal feedback + coaching 2-4 weeks Level 2: Written Warning No improvement after coaching OR score 1.5-1.9 Documented warning 2 weeks Level 3: PIP No improvement after warning OR score &lt;1.5 Formal PIP document 30 days Level 4: Separation PIP goals not met OR gross misconduct Termination Immediate or per contract /* Section 2: Level 1 - Coaching Process */ 2 . Level 1: Coaching Process When to use: First sign of underperformance, minor issues, skill gaps Steps: 1. Private conversation Describe the issue with specific examples 2. Listen Ask for their perspective, understand root cause 3. Agree on solution What needs to change, what support is needed 4. Set check-in date Usually 2-4 weeks 5. Document Brief notes in employee file (date, issue, agreed actions) Outcome: If improved → return to normal. If not → escalate to Level 2. /* Section 3: Level 2 - Written Warning */ 3 . Level 2: Written Warning When to use: Coaching didn&apos;t work, or issue is more serious Written Warning Must Include: Date and employee name Specific performance issues (with examples) Previous coaching attempts (dates, what was discussed) Expected improvement (specific, measurable) Timeline for improvement (usually 2 weeks) Consequences if not improved (PIP) Employee signature acknowledging receipt Outcome: If improved → return to normal (warning stays on file 6 months). If not → escalate to PIP. /* Section 4: Level 3 - Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) */ 4 . Level 3: Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) When to use: Serious performance issues, pattern of underperformance, written warning didn&apos;t work PIP Document Must Include: Section Contents Performance Gaps Specific issues with data/examples from evaluations Success Criteria SMART goals — what &quot;success&quot; looks like at end of PIP Support Provided Training, resources, additional check-ins, mentor Check-in Schedule Weekly meetings during 30-day period Timeline 30 days (start and end date) Consequences Clear statement: failure to meet goals may result in termination Signatures Employee, Manager/Founder, HR (if applicable) Outcome: If goals met → PIP closed, return to normal monitoring. If not → separation. /* Section 5: Immediate Termination (Gross Misconduct) */ 5 . Immediate Termination (Gross Misconduct) Some behaviors bypass the progressive discipline process and result in immediate termination: Theft or fraud Violence or threats of violence Harassment or discrimination Sharing confidential client information Intentional damage to company property or reputation Working while under influence of drugs/alcohol /* Section 6: Documentation & Storage */ 6 . Documentation & Storage All records stored: HR folder (restricted access — Founder only) Coaching notes: Kept for 6 months after resolution Written warnings: Kept for 1 year after resolution PIP documents: Kept for duration of employment + 2 years Termination records: Kept permanently /* Footer */ Owner: Founder ); coaching pip performance improvement plan warning termination discipline misconduct underperformance sop hr written warning separation feedback correction"
